entry.title: VC UI: Register delegate for audio effects if needed
entry.content:
There might be a case when we add noise cancellation effect in the

middle of a session and the delegate has not been registered yet (since

there's no effect added during OnActiveUserPrefServiceChanged).

In this case, we need to register the delegate when adding the effect.

Instead of register delegate in OnActiveUserPrefServiceChanged, we will

now register delegate if needed each time we add an effect.

entry.title: gpu: Fix potential CurrentGL dangling pointer
entry.content:
There's a potential issue with GLContextEGL::ReleaseBackpressureFences

leaving the thread local CurrentGL pointer set if there was no previous

current context. This means that the pointer will be dangling when the

context is destroyed. This ordinarily doesn't happen with Ganesh/GL

since there's almost always a current GL context, but it's possible with

Graphite when SharedContext won't ever make its context current.



This CL also cleans up the code related to setting the thread local

CurrentGL pointer:



- GetGlContextForCurrentThread returns a reference to the thread local

CurrentGL pointer so it's renamed to ThreadLocalCurrentGL and is

not exposed via gl_bindings.h (see below).

- GetThreadLocalCurrentGL returns the CurrentGL pointer and is exported

in gl_bindings.h. It does not return a mutable reference though.

- SetCurrentGL sets the thread local CurrentGL pointer so it's renamed

to SetThreadLocalCurrentGL to distinguish it from GetCurrentGL which

is an accessor on the GLContext class.

entry.title: Re-land: CHECK that style and layout are not left dirty during lifecycle
entry.content:
The first iteration of this patch, https://crrev.com/1192759, was

reverted due to scroll animations leaving style and layout dirty

(https://crbug.com/1478009). This turns out to be working as intended

so this patch moves the cleanliness check below

`RunScrollSnapshotClientSteps`.



Original change description below:

`LocalFrameView::UpdateLifecyclePhasesInternal` is responsible for

running the lifecycle and uses the following high-level pattern:

while (true) {

RunStyleAndLayoutLifecyclePhases();



bool needs_to_repeat_lifecycle = RunStepA();

if (needs_to_repeat_lifecycle) { continue; }



bool needs_to_repeat_lifecycle = RunStepB();

if (needs_to_repeat_lifecycle) { continue; }

...

}

Each step expects clean style and layout, and if a step dirties style

or layout, it should re-start the lifecycle. This patch adds CHECKs for

many of the lifecycle steps which ensures style and layout are not left

dirty. These checks are added inside functions when possible, to

provide more helpful crash stacks.

the route ends.

MirroringMediaControllerHostImpl, and handling the delay using a

OneShotTimer that can be cancelled upon the route ending early.

1) Rename safebrowsingv5_alpha1.proto to safebrowsingv5.proto

2) Remove the `filter` in SearchHashesRequest. Remove SUSPICIOUS and

SOCIAL_ENGINEERING_ADS from ThreatType.

3) Change the SearchHashes endpoint to https://safebrowsing.googleapis.com/v5/hashes:search.

4) Because of the removal of SUSPICIOUS threat type, we need to map

SOCIAL_ENGINEERING + CANARY back to SB_THREAT_TYPE_SUSPICIOUS_SITE.

This change is reflected in the MapFullHashDetailToSbThreatType

function.



Currently the backend will only set CANARY for

ABUSIVE_EXPERIENCE_VIOLATION, BETTER_ADS_VIOLATION, API_ABUSE and

SOCIAL_ENGINEERING (only SOCIAL_ENGINEERING is relevant to this CL

since others are not frame URLs. Chrome should discard the whole

FullHashDetail if CANARY is seen with other threat type (e.g. MALWARE).



If CANARY and FRAME_ONLY are both presented in one single

FullHashDetail, Chrome should discard it.



This change will not be gated by a separate flag. Going forward, HPRT

for SSB (SafeBrowsingHashPrefixRealTimeLookups) and the experiment on

ESB users (SafeBrowsingLookupMechanismExperiment) will be reaching the

GA endpoint.

entry.title: [dPWA] Fix ghost apps created due to policy installs with error URL load
entry.content:
As a remnant of crbug.com/1440946, some app install URLs returning a

503 error or other HTTP error were treated as success, leading to apps

being installed with the install URL as a start URL, and appearing as

valid apps, i.e. not a placeholder. As a result, deduping those apps

into existing installed apps were not possible, since to the web apps

system, that happened to be valid.



This CL attempts to fix the above use-case where:

1. There is a policy app where install URL == start URL and it's not

a placeholder.

2. The same install URL with a default query is installed as a separate app.



If both cases satisfy, the fix will wipe out the erroneous policy apps

and merge both the apps into the latest installed one (policy) with

all information deduped. This is done by introducing a new web_app DB

field called latest_install_time, which gets updated everytime a new

install happens. Consequently, the install_time field is renamed to

first_install_time, which accounts for when the app was first installed.



Bug: 1440946, b/298039499

entry.title: [MDL] Add metrics for size and initialization time
entry.content:
The contents of the Masked Domain List are used in multiple Network

Service classes and the list is expected to grow considerably in the

future. These metrics are being added to evaluate its impact on the

startup time of the Network Service, success of updates, and estimated

memory usage of the MDL-derived NetworkServiceProxyAllowList and

NetworkServiceResourceBlockList as new features utilizing them are

enabled and the list grows.



The individual instances of the matcher classes in `//net` are not

expected to use much memory but it may begin to add up if there are

hundreds or thousands of entries in the MDL that each require their own

rules.



These estimation methods do not work for Cronet builds, so the affected

`//net` classes hide the method in that case. The Network Service

classes are not used by Cronet, so these new histograms should not be

affected.

entry.title: [AppList] Fix crash on toast view fade out animation
entry.content:
When FadeOutToastView() is called during an already initiated fade out

animation, a crash occurs because the toast_view_ is deleted when the

first animation is aborted. Fix this by aborting the animation using

an abort handle, then check that toast_view_ still exists before

initiating the fade out animation.



Also, disable the close button on the toast view after the first

click, to avoid a call to CommitTemporarySortOrder() multiple times

in a row. Check that the current sort order is temporary before

attempting to commit the new order.



Finally, simplify the code path to commit the sort order by calling

directly into the app list model updater similar to the path for when

the reorder undo button is clicked.



Low-Coverage-Reason: chrome_app_list_model_updater functionality remains the same.

entry.title: [bookmarks] Introduce UUID-keyed index in BookmarkModel
entry.content:
An increasing number of features make use of bookmark UUIDs and rely on

UUID-based lookups, as represented by the utility functions modified in

this patch (will be deleted in upcoming patches as they became trivial).



Instead, this patch introduces a new API in BookmarkModel that is

powered by a newly-introduced index that allows efficient lookups

(instead of exhaustively iterating the bookmark tree).



Given that the new lookups are very efficient, it now becomes possible

for BookmarkModel to verify that the UUID-uniquess invariant holds

true, instrumented via DUMP_WILL_BE_CHECK (preferred over CHECKs due

to past issues that motivated https://crrev.com/c/2506030).
